column11:
  This paper is concerned with the following system of elliptic equations
{equation*}
  \{{array}{ll}
  -\Delta u+u= F_u(|x|,u,v), & \hbox{}
  -\Delta v+v=- F_v(|x|,u,v), & \hbox{}
  \,\,\,\,\,u,v\in H^1(\mathbb{R}^N). & \hbox{}
  {array}. {equation*} It is shown that if $F$ is odd in $(u,v)$ and satisfy
some growth conditions, then $(\mathcal{S})$ has infinitely many both radial
and nonradial solutions. The proof relies on the Principle of Symmetric
Criticality and a generalized Fountain Theorem for strongly indefinite
functionals.
